<body>

<h1>@KJ{{direction}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vmasustem{{}} @KJ{{direction}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong> forms a noun from the @HI{{masu}} stem of a verb.
</p>

<p>
The meaning can be either "way" or "manner" and is determined by the context.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KT{{ke-ki}}no @KJ{{make}}ri<strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong>wo @KJ{{teach}}ete kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Please show me how to make a cake.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
Sino-Japanese @HI{{suru}} verbs take the particle @HI{{no}} before @HI{{shi<strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong>}},
for example @KJ{{electricity^tale}}@HI{{no shi}}<strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}no @KJ{{exertion^strong}}no@KJ{{attend}}<strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong>wo
    @KJ{{teach}}ete kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Please teach me how to learn Japanese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
When <strong>@KJ{{direction}}</strong> means "method", it can be replaced by <strong>@KJ{{direction^method}}</strong>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}no @KJ{{exertion^strong}}no<strong>@KJ{{direction^method}}</strong>wo @KJ{{teach}}ete kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Please teach me a method to learn Japanese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

